fields.title: Hello, World! - Python
fields.subtitle: Hello, World!
fields.description:
Python is a very simple language, and has a very straightforward syntax. It encourages programmers to program without boilerplate (prepared) code. The simplest directive in Python is the "print" directive - it simply prints out a line (and also includes a newline, unlike in C).

There are two major Python versions, Python 2 and Python 3. Python 2 and 3 are quite different. This tutorial uses Python 3, because it more semantically correct and supports newer features.

fields.title: Variables and Types
fields.subtitle: Variables and Types
fields.description:
Python is completely object oriented, and not "statically typed". You do not need to declare variables before using them, or declare their type. Every variable in Python is an object.

This tutorial will go over a few basic types of variables.

fields.title: Lists Python
fields.subtitle: Lists Python
fields.description:
Lists are very similar to arrays. They can contain any type of variable, and they can contain as many variables as you wish. Lists can also be iterated over in a very simple manner. Here is an example of how to build a list.

In this exercise, you will need to add numbers and strings to the correct lists using the "append" list method. You must add the numbers 1,2, and 3 to the "numbers" list, and the words 'hello' and 'world' to the strings variable.

fields.title: Basic Operators
fields.subtitle: Basic Operators
fields.description:
Arithmetic Operators

Just as any other programming languages, the addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division operators can be used with numbers.

fields.title: String Formatting
fields.subtitle: String Formatting
fields.description:
Python uses C-style string formatting to create new, formatted strings. 

The "%" operator is used to format a set of variables enclosed in a 
"tuple" (a fixed size list), together with a format string, which contains normal text together with 
"argument specifiers", special symbols like "%s" and "%d".

fields.title: A Word about Those UFO Videos
fields.subtitle: IÆm an astrophysicist, but that doesnÆt mean I have a motivation to debunk them
fields.description:
IÆm not going to debunk the PentagonÆs recently declassified UFO videos.

ItÆs not that I think theyÆre actually aliens. ItÆs not even that I think theyÆre unexplainable, or that theyÆre obviously some particular thing or other. And although science communication experts frequently debate the effectiveness of debunking as a strategy, thatÆs not the source of my reluctance either. ItÆs because for an astrophysicist like me, thereÆs very little motivation to do it.

You might be surprised at this. IÆm a scientist! I want to know how things work! I am interested in mysteries, and this is a mystery about space, right?

Well, no. This is a set of videos recorded by instruments in a military aircraft, showing indistinct objects within the EarthÆs atmosphere. The real explanation for them is almost certainly going to be something well outside my main area of expertise, which includes cosmic phenomena such as the behavior of dark matter in galaxies and the extreme conditions of the early universe. While IÆm interested in technology and physics in general, IÆm not a military tech aficionado, and while weird atmospheric optical effects are interesting, thatÆs not really what gets me out of bed in the morning.

fields.title: How to Grow as a (Software) Engineering Manager
fields.subtitle: How to Grow as a (Software) Engineering Manager
fields.description:
When discussing their journey as engineers, managers, VP, or CTO with my friends, colleagues, and peers, a striking observation always remains: thereÆs a vast diversity of journeys.

I used the word ôjourneyö intentionally and not ôcareer,ö as I prefer that framing. I find it particularly restricting to picture progress as a ôcareer ladder,ö in which youÆd have to tick the boxes to climb to the next level. A ladder is a possible way to visualise that journey, but I encourage everyone to question what their journey should be.

The main issue that I see with the concept of ôladderö is two-fold. First, it suggests that the higher, the better (analogous to similar organisational considerations IÆve always found awful). Second, it indicates that the journey is dramatically linear. To formulate a couple of other criticisms, it also suggests a form of ôthe sooner, the better,ö and even worse to me; it implies that thereÆs a final rung you can reach (yes, ôthe end,ö my friends).

fields.title: A Ten-Step Process for Team Leaders to Reduce Meeting Overload and Take Back Their Time
fields.subtitle: My blueprint (which you should steal) for freeing your time
fields.description:
A few months ago, I started a new job as the leader of a busy team of consultants. Within days of starting, I found myself inundated with meetings, and the expectation seemed to be that I represent our team at board meetings, client meetings, external engagements, you name it.

Being eager to please my new boss, itÆs a role IÆve happily played, with little thought to the consequences.

But increasingly IÆve found myself frustrated, compensating for my busy diary by doing all high value work between 06:00 am and 09:00 am, then staying late to mop up the emails IÆve missed during the day ù because IÆve been in back-to-back meetings.

While it increasingly appears to be the norm that people work longer hours to keep up, itÆs hard to add any real value or critical thought when I spend my days surfing from meeting to meeting. And interestingly, my team has begun to mention that they would like me to provide more guidance on their work, which obviously I canÆt do if IÆm always in meetings.

ItÆs been tempting to shrug my shoulders and think ôhey, this is just the meeting culture of the organizationö. But IÆve realized that this is a lazy response and poor leadership.
